I admit that I was caught speeding with my brand-new car out of curiosity to test its speed. While I understand that this curiosity was not an excuse for my actions, I now fully recognize the severity of my behavior and the potential consequences it could have caused.

I take full responsibility for my negligence in disregarding the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP). Admittedly, I have a habit of not thoroughly reading my mail, which led to me missing the NIP. I deeply regret my carelessness and acknowledge that had I seen the notice, I would have promptly responded and addressed the situation as required.

In regards to my driving history, I do have a record of three previous speeding incidents on my license. I genuinely regret these past offenses and understand the importance of being mindful on the road. However, it is important to note that other than these driving offenses, I have a clean record. I also want to bring to the court's attention that I have been diagnosed with ADHD, which may have influenced my impulsive decision-making on the day of the offense. While I am aware that ADHD does not excuse my actions, I believe it is important for the court to consider this factor when evaluating my case.

I am fully cognizant of the impact of my actions, and I am committed to taking the necessary steps to prevent similar offenses in the future. I have made arrangements to seek support and guidance to effectively manage my ADHD and improve my decision-making skills. My aim is to ensure that I do not pose a risk to myself or others on the road.

In conclusion, Your Honor, I accept full responsibility for my offense and deeply regret the potential harm I caused. I kindly request the court to consider my acknowledgement of my ADHD and my commitment to personal growth as mitigating factors when determining an appropriate sentence.

Thank you for your attention.

Sincerely,

