Your Honor,

I stand before you today to plead guilty to the offense of speeding. I want to express my sincere remorse for my reckless behavior and acknowledge the potential danger I posed to others.

I admit that I was caught speeding with my brand-new car out of curiosity to test its speed. While I understand that this curiosity was not an excuse for my actions, I now fully recognize the severity of my behavior and the potential consequences it could have caused.

I take full responsibility for failing to respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP). I regrettably have a habit of not thoroughly reading my mail, which led to me missing the NIP. I understand that this negligence on my part is inexcusable, and I am deeply sorry for failing to address the situation as required.

In regards to my driving history, I do have a record of three previous speeding incidents on my license. I genuinely regret these past offenses and acknowledge the importance of being mindful on the road. However, it is important to note that other than these driving offenses, I have a clean record.

Furthermore, I wanted to inform the court that I have been diagnosed with ADHD. While I understand that ADHD does not excuse my actions, I believe it is important for the court to consider this factor when evaluating my case. The impulsive decision-making characteristic of ADHD may have played a role in my behavior on the day of the offense.

I am fully cognizant of the impact of my actions, and I kindly request the court's leniency based on my acknowledgement of my ADHD. I assure the court that I am committed to being more vigilant on the road and taking the necessary steps to prevent similar offenses in the future.

In conclusion, Your Honor, I accept full responsibility for my offense and deeply regret the potential harm I caused. Thank you for your attention.

Sincerely,

