1068
Your Honor,

I humbly appear before you today to plead guilty to the offense of speeding. I want to express my sincere remorse for my reckless actions and the potential danger they imposed on others.

I acknowledge that I was caught speeding in my brand-new car out of curiosity to test its speed. While I understand that curiosity is not a valid excuse for my behavior, I have come to fully grasp the gravity of my actions and the potential consequences they could have incurred.

I take full responsibility for my failure to respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP). Regrettably, I have a tendency to neglect reading my mail thoroughly, and as a result, I missed the NIP. I am well aware that this negligence on my part is inexcusable, and I sincerely apologize for not addressing the matter as required.

In terms of my driving record, it is important for the court to consider that I have three previous incidents of speeding on my license. I deeply regret these past offenses and understand the significance of driving responsibly. However, it is crucial to note that apart from these driving-related transgressions, I have a clean record.

Additionally, I would like to bring to the court's attention that I have been diagnosed with ADHD. Although ADHD does not absolve me of responsibility for my actions, I believe it is essential for the court to take this into consideration when evaluating my case. The impulsive decision-making characteristic of ADHD may have influenced my behavior on the day of the offense.

I am fully mindful of the impact of my actions, and I humbly request the court's leniency given the circumstances surrounding my ADHD. I assure the court that I am committed to exercising greater vigilance on the road and taking the necessary measures to prevent any future transgressions.

To conclude, Your Honor, I wholeheartedly accept responsibility for my offense, and I deeply regret the potential harm I caused. Thank you for your attention.

Respectfully,

Robert Chapman
